text: Is there a way to use marker based folds on top of syntax based folds? (Where is the definition for how marker folds works? Hard-coded?) They don't work when fdm=syntax, at least not that I'm seeing. Oh, note I said marker, not manual. But I can't use zf to create a fold when fdm=syntax either. Yeah, I don't think I can either. Which is sort of why I was hoping the fdm=marker fold definitions were lying around in some file somewhere that I could just grab and add myself, but I sort of doubt they are. I meant the syntax (or what-have-you) definitions which tell vim to fold them. This is C, I found the normal block fold syntax stuff, but I can't find anywhere that does the marker folds. Yes, but something needs to tell vim to actually fold those. Which happens when you :set fdm=marker and doesn't when you :set fdm=something_else. That was part of the question, is the fdm=marker magic in the source or in some file. (runtime file) I wouldn't be, the syntax folds are all in runtime files, this could be as well. Which isn't to say that it is.

iowait is idle CPU that nobody else but processes waiting for IO would want to use, afaik? (so if there were any CPU-hungry processes, iowait would be 0) Thus, in and of itself, iowait isn't a problem - it's free CPU that nobody wants. But it's an indication that your IO subsystem is a bottleneck. Ask iostat which disk is 100% blocking =) http://www.xfree86.org/current/fc-cache.1.html - if we're talking about the same fc-cache, it's indexing. And it sounds like something that could cause some pretty heavy random io load. =) It's a pain on the first run, but you'll probably benefit from it later. =) pkill -STOP fc-cache and see if things ease? =) hm. swap trashing hell?

If that stuff starts before the font caches exist, it tends to behave badly. perhaps run fc-cache -v, wait it out, then restart the stuff that maybe making use of it? Hi CSS3 selectors specification defines {simple_selector_sequence} as follows: [ type_selector | universal ] [ HASH | class | attrib | pseudo | negation ]* | [ HASH | class | attrib | pseudo | negation ]+ why there is no '*' or '+' or '?' sign after [ type_selector | universal ] ? does it mean that there should be exactly one {type_selector} or {universal} at the start of  {simple_selector_sequence}? this would mean that something like '#header' is not a simple selector no, wait... it makes sense... s/one of both/one from the two "A sequence of simple selectors is a chain of simple selectors that are not separated by a combinator. It always begins with a type selector or a universal selector. No other type selector or universal selector is allowed in the sequence." now I'm confused, selectors starting with '.blah' or '#blah' are not a sequence of simple selectors? "If a universal selector represented by * (i.e. without a namespace prefix) is not the only component of a sequence of simple selectors selectors or is immediately followed by a pseudo-element, then the * may be omitted and the universal selector's presence implied." so the grammar definition is wrong? It assumes that universal selector or type selector are always there it doesn't take into account the fact that universal selector's presence might be implied

c63a5cfce0a1819ebbe4a19e074356b6: "#header" matches HASH so it matches "[HASH | ...]+" so it matches "... | [HASH | ...]+", I think c63a5cfce0a1819ebbe4a19e074356b6: [ A | B ] means either A, or B (not both, and not neither) I think the grouping is equivalent to "[ [type_selector|universal] [stuff]* ] | [stuff]+", not like "[type_selector|universal] [ [stuff]* | [stuff]+ ]" so if you don't have type_selector or universal, you need at least one of the stuff (i.e. you can't just have the empty string)

c6abb49e663030403f65db047e2cb714, would delaying script execution be really bad? c6abb49e663030403f65db047e2cb714, similarly to how it's done for layout today? several engines at least first compute layout before returning offsetLeft or something for instance true, don't know whether that matters maybe it should delay but there should also be an event that would be the recommended usage pattern? I don't really want sessionStorage / localStorage to become async in Opera it wouldn't block the UI but I gues that's a problem other browsers have, yes

edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: how do you delay it? edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: in that case you're not waiting for IO, however edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: in general I would think that waiting for a read from disk could take much longer than a layout could edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: if you allow authors to read before the event, then I don't think they'll ever wait for the event 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c: yeah, waiting to start script execution seems a little better than pausing during script execution

edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e, c6abb49e663030403f65db047e2cb714: if you are talking about localStorage, all you have to do is wait for the local storage data (if there is any for that site) to load from disk before you start running the first script that's the same as waiting for the data for an external script pretty much not quite the same thing as the offsetLeft case, which is stopping in the middle of script execution I don't think the API needs to be async, just the implementation pausing during script execution blocks the UI waiting on I/O, which is bad and you can also have a master index of which sites have any per-site data, so you'd know up front whether the possible disk read is even needed

coffman: Hard drives won't save me from a fire that takes out my computer.  Unless it's an external drive, which isn't quite as cheap. An internal drive (to which I can sync) and ZFS snapshots will save me from software failures.  Mirroring will save me from simply hardware failures.  I'm currently concerned about catastrophic hardware failures.  My current data contains 10+ years of personal data that I really, really don't want to lose. 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, put it this way: there's such a thing as having too many tests.  You reach that point when the cost of running the extra tests outweighs the benefit of realistically catching any extra bugs.  For manual tests, that threshold is very, very low, since they're so expensive to write and run. How about when I run out of things to do, you assign me to write a basic spec for cross-browser UI testing, like with click simulation or whatever? I imagine it wouldn't be hard to implement the few most basic things in at least one browser. (not that I'm saying I'll do that part, but maybe someone will be interested in doing it quickly) (I'm still writing some more manual tests here, but I think it's a bad idea to write more than a few.) a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554, Watir requires you to use Ruby, yes?  That's a pretty massive minus. We'd really want JavaScript tests that can be run straight from the browser, like Mochitests. It's also a bit weird for the tests for a spec to depend on a particular program implementation in a particular non-standard language. Does anyone know how WebKit does it? 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c, how does WebKit do tests that require synthesizing user input like keypresses or mouse clicks? Are these methods called from simple JavaScript code within WebKit, like Gecko does it, or is it some external program? Ah, so like Gecko, then. It would be nice to expose some of those in a safe way to spec tests, yes?  There are lots of things you can't do automated tests for without them. For instance, require a command-line option that specifies the URL prefixes that are allowed to use them, say. So you could whitelist http://dvcs.w3.org/ or whatever. Yeah, I guess that's not safe enough. Also, lots of people have commit access to there. Well, it's only got to be as safe as running the tests that browsers already have. But it's doable, even if it would require downloading the test locally and running the browser with a command-line switch pointing at the exact local file you want to run (but I hope we can make it more convenient than that). twincest: works for me, always has bootable pure ZFS is not currently available, yes you need a small partition of some writtable file system that grub and solaris both understand twincest: ah that part of the tab completion I've never tried only the hd0 bits loke: no it doesn't it requires a ufs partition of the grub and boot-archive stuff to live in. the rest of the root file system can be on a mirrored zpool but it changes so very rarely that you might as well just do that with dd manually in theory you should be able to do this with a pcfs file system stored on a USB drive and you could have two USB drives as your detached mirrors :-) If you want this for real, it is best to wait very much so, see the archives of zfs-discuss that point you to the status and to the blog entries of the people doing the work. I've seen code in progress for zfs support in grub and it is surprisingly very simple. it doesn't need to support write so that cuts out all the COW complexity it also only supports single device or mirrors so none of the raidz stuff needs to be in there. in ZFS you don't make stripes like you do in VxVM or SVM I'm not sure if you can boot from an un mirrored pool that has multiple disks in it see the zfs-discuss email archives for the info,  IIRC this was asked previously loke: welcome to open development where you see things before they are finished :-)
